Renaissance Church from 1483 with Art from Caravaggio & Raphael Inside
Dec 2023 • Couples
The Basilica of Saint Augustine dates back to 1483 and features Renaissance architecture. Inside is artwork from masters such as Caravaggio & Raphael. Free admission but limited opening hours from 9-1130am and 4-5pm. Easy to miss in an area where it seems like there is a church around every corner and with Rome highlights like the Pantheon and Piazza Navona nearby.

Art filled basilica at Piazza di Sant' Agostino
Mar 2024 • Family
The Basilica of Sant' Agostino is located on the square by the same name and is a short distance northeast of Piazza Navona. It has a history dating back to the 14th-century while the building you see today is considered one of Rome's first Renaissance churches and there are some important artworks found within including an altar designed by Bernini, pillar fresco by Raphael and the 'Madonna of the Pilgrims' masterpiece by Caravaggio (1604). The interior is heavily frescoed and ornately decorated. It is a nice church to include in your sightseeing if you want to view nice art and like visiting historic churches.

United Kingdom11,518 contributions
On the Caravaggio Trail….
Jun 2022
You’d be forgiven for walking past this imposing but austere, grey facade and not stopping to go inside.
I was making a beeline for it because of the Caravaggio painting of the Madonna di Loreto. I’d already visited the nearby Church of San Luigi dei Francesi which has 3 Caravaggio works so I was hot on the Caravaggio trail (they are only 3 minutes walk apart).
This Caravaggio is tucked away in the first side chapel on the left (the Cavalletti Chapel). The lighting here is not great but even so, there is something very special about seeing a painting like this in its original location rather than isolated on a white wall in a gallery.
It’s hard to believe now but this conventional looking religious scene of Mary holding her child, Jesus once attracted controversy. Outrage was sparked by the pilgrims’ bare, dirty feet. Realistically, pilgrims who had traipsed along dusty roads for great distances were likely to be looking a little scruffy. It was hardly surprising that they were in need of a good bath and a pedicure. Nevertheless, in some circles it was considered scandalous to put such shabby looking people on the same canvas as Mary, the mother of Christ. To make it worse, many felt that Mary herself was looking dangerously like a regular person. Neither her clothing nor the subtle almost-not-there halo set her apart or distinguished her as the mother of Christ.
The Caravaggio was the highlight for me but its not the only significant artwork.
Sansovino's ‘Madonna del Parto’ is near the entrance.
Just past the Caravaggio, is a Raphael fresco of the prophet, Isaiah flanked by two chubby cherubs. It’s a relatively small painting on the pillar and sits above eye level so it doesn’t leap out at you and you can walk past if you’re not looking for it.
Below that is a marble sculpture of the Virgin Mary, with baby Jesus and St Anne also by Andrea Sansovino.
Beside the high altar (the chapel on the left)is the tomb of the popular St Monica, mother of St Augustine, is here (in the chapel to the left of the high altar).
Overall, this is a beautiful church to visit and because its not on the mainstream tourist radar, it is uncrowded and peaceful.
Written March 7, 2023

dapper777
Monaco66,929 contributions
Not to be missed when in Rome
Sep 2019 • Friends
Not far from the craziness that is Piazza Navona and from the Church of San Luigi dei Francesi (which has three works by Caravaggio), the church is squeezed between two streets sheltered by an arch.
The façade is very simple and sober (inspired by Santa Maria Novella in Florence) but the interior is imposing.
It is the typical example of Roman Renaissance architecture.
It was built in 1483 using some of the travertine blocks which had fallen from the Colosseum.
On the third pillar on the left side of the nave you will see an important fresco by Raphael, the Prophet Isaiah (1512). Underneath the fresco is a lovely marble group with Virgin Mary, Child and St Anne (1512) always by Andrea Sansovino.
On the high altar, made in 1627 by Bernini, is located the Virgin with Child coming from the church of Santa Sophia in Constantinople.
In the Cavalletti Chapel (first chaple on the left) there is a very important and beautiful work of art, the absolutely magnificent Madonna di Loreto (also known as Madonna dei Pellegrini, Madonna of the pilgrims) by Caravaggio.
Above the entrance door the huge organ, remodeled several times.
Next to it, there is the statue of Madonna del Parto (Our Lady of Childbirth) by Jacopo Sansovino (1521), which would be miraculous in childbirth.
In fact the statue is laden with votive offerings, ex-voto's, flowers, candles and many blue and pink ribbons and bows hanging on the walls, offered by parents asking for (or thanking for) a safe childbirth (a blue ribbon means a boy, a pink ribbon means a girl).
According to a legend, the statue was made by adapting an ancient effigy that portrays roman empress Agrippina holding her son Nero in her arms.
Many women offer their prayers here in hopes of ensuring a safe childbirth.
It shows the Blessed Mother holding the baby Jesus.
The tomb of Saint Monica is another attraction here. It preserves her relics. Saint Monica, the mother of Saint Augustine is entombed in the chapel to the left of the high altar.
Unfortunately, although she is such a popular saint, not many people are aware that her tomb is in this church.
Particularly important is the altarpiece depicting “St. Augustine with John the Baptist and St Paul the Hermit”, 1638, located in the third chapel on the right and dedicated to the saint to whom the church was named after.
The church is never crowded, the hordes of tourists prefer more popular attractions on their overbeaten tourist paths.
As a result, you normally do not have to worry about crowds.
We highly recommend that you include this church in your Rome map
Written April 17, 2020
